rstand the Situation”: Asia Strategy and Escalation in Vietnam, 1961–1968 -- t9. “An Even Balance”: Nixon and Kissinger’s Redefinition of Containment in Asia, 1969–1975 -- t10. “The President Cannot Make Any Weak Moves”: Jimmy Carter and the Return of the China Card, 1977–1980 -- t11. “To Contain and Over Time Reverse”: Ronald Reagan, 1980–1989 -- tPART FOUR THE RISE OF CHINA -- t12. “The Key to Our Security and Our Prosperity Lies in the Vitality of Those Relationships”: George H. W. Bush and the Unipolar Moment, 1989–1992 -- t13. “Engage and Balance”: Bill Clinton and the Unexpected Return of Great- Power Politics -- t14. “A Balance of Power That Favors Freedom”: Strategic Surprise and the Asia Policy of George W. Bush -- t15. “The Pivot”: Barack Obama and the Struggle to Rebalance to Asia -- tConclusion: The Historical Case for Asia Strategy -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSoon after the American Revolution, ?certain of the founders began to recognize the strategic significance of Asia and the Pacific and the vast material and cultural resources at stake there. Over the coming generations, the United States continued to ask how best to expand trade with the region and whether to partner with China, at the center of the continent, or Japan, looking toward the Pacific. Where should the United States draw its defensive line, and how should it export democratic principles? In a history that spans the eighteenth century to the present, Michael J. Green follows the development of U.S. strategic thinking toward East Asia, identifying recurring themes in American statecraft that reflect the nation's political philosophy and material realities.Drawing on archives, interviews, and his own experience in the Pentagon and White House, Green finds one overarching concern driving U.S. policy toward East Asia: a fear that a rival power might use the Pacific to isolate and threaten the United States and prevent the ocean from becoming a conduit for the westward free flow of trade, values, and forward defense. By More Than Providence works through these problems from the perspective of history's major strategists and statesmen, from Thomas Jefferson to Alfred Thayer Mahan and Henry Kissinger. It records the fate of their ideas as they collided with the realities of the Far East and adds clarity to America's stakes in the region, especially when compared with those of Europe and the Middle East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2017z9783110548242oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/gree1804240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231542722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231542722/original  a978-3-11-054330-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2017  aZDB-23-DSWb2